# Command agent

## What does this command do:

Cursor CLI lets you interact with AI agents directly from your terminal to write, review, and modify code. Whether you prefer an interactive terminal interface or print automation for scripts and CI pipelines

Also installed as legacy alias: cursor-agent

## Installed from

For Fedora install using: curl https://cursor.com/install -fsS | bash
For Raspberry Pi install using: curl https://cursor.com/install -fsS | bash
For Mac install using: curl https://cursor.com/install -fsS | bash

## Command path

For Fedora run: ~/.local/bin/agent
For Raspberry Pi run: ~/.local/bin/agent
For Mac run: ~/.local/bin/agent

## Command documentation

Docs can be found at https://cursor.com/cli

## Command options

# Start interactive session
agent

# Start with an initial prompt
agent "refactor this file to use async/await"

# Non-interactive / scripting / CI mode (print response and exit)
agent --print "explain this function"
agent -p "what does main.go do?"

# Output formats (only with --print)
agent --print --output-format text "prompt"
agent --print --output-format json "prompt"
agent --print --output-format stream-json --stream-partial-output "prompt"

# Execution modes
agent --mode plan "design a new auth module"   # read-only planning, no edits
agent --mode ask  "how does this work?"        # Q&A, read-only
agent --plan      "shorthand for --mode=plan"

# Model selection
agent --model sonnet-4 "prompt"
agent --model sonnet-4-thinking "prompt"
agent --list-models

# Session management
agent --resume              # pick a session to resume (interactive)
agent --resume <chatId>     # resume specific session by ID
agent --continue            # continue most recent session
agent ls                    # list previous chat sessions
agent resume                # resume latest chat session
agent create-chat           # create a new empty chat and return its ID

# Authentication
agent login
agent logout
agent status                # show auth status / whoami
agent about                 # version, system, and account info

# MCP servers
agent mcp                   # manage MCP servers
agent --approve-mcps "prompt"  # auto-approve all MCP servers

# Git worktrees (isolated environments)
agent --worktree            # start in an auto-named isolated git worktree
agent -w my-feature         # start in a named worktree
agent --worktree-base main  # base the worktree on a specific branch/ref

# Force / trust flags (use with caution)
agent --force               # allow all commands unless explicitly denied
agent --yolo                # alias for --force
agent --trust               # trust workspace without prompting (headless only)
agent --sandbox enabled     # override sandbox mode
agent --sandbox disabled

# Workspace
agent --workspace /path/to/project "prompt"

# Specify API key inline (or use CURSOR_API_KEY env var)
agent --api-key <key> "prompt"

# Add custom request headers
agent -H "X-Custom: value" "prompt"

# Shell integration
agent install-shell-integration    # adds integration to ~/.zshrc
agent uninstall-shell-integration  # removes it

# Update
agent update
